SOLID Principle:
    SOLID principles in Java are 5 core design principles that help you write clean, maintainable, scalable, and testable code. 
    They are widely used in object-oriented programming.

1. S – Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) -> A class should have only one reason to change.
   Meaning: One class = one job.
   Example (Bad):
          class Employee {
              void calculateSalary() {}
              void saveToDatabase() {}
          }
   Example (Good):
        class Employee {
            void calculateSalary() {}
        }
        
        class EmployeeRepository {
            void save(Employee emp) {}
        }
       ✔ Improves readability and maintainability

2. O – Open/Closed Principle (OCP) - Open for extension, closed for modification.
    Meaning: You should add new functionality without changing existing code.
    Example:
        interface Shape {
            double area();
        }      
        class Circle implements Shape {
            public double area() { return 3.14 * 2 * 2; }
        }
        class Rectangle implements Shape {
            public double area() { return 4 * 5; }
        }  
      ✔ Add new shapes without modifying old code

3. L – Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) - Subclasses should replace parent classes without breaking behavior.
    Meaning: Child class must behave like parent. 
    Bad Example:
        class Bird {
            void fly() {}
        } 
        class Ostrich extends Bird {
            void fly() { throw new UnsupportedOperationException(); }
        }
    Good Design: 
        class Bird {}
        class FlyingBird extends Bird {
            void fly() {}
        
        class Ostrich extends Bird {}
    ✔ Avoid unexpected behavior

4. I – Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) - Don't force a class to implement methods it doesn't use.
    Meaning: A class should not be forced to implement methods it doesn’t need. 
    In simple words: Instead of one big interface, create small, specific interfaces.
    Real-life example:
      Think of a printer: 
            Some printers only print
            Some print + scan
      You shouldn’t force a simple printer to implement scanning. 
    Java idea:  
        ❌ Bad: One interface with many methods
        ✔ Good: Split into smaller interfaces so each class uses only what it needs
    Bad Example:
        interface Worker {
            void work();
            void eat();
        }  
    Good Example:
        interface Workable {
            void work();
        } 
        interface Eatable {
            void eat();
        }
    ✔ Smaller, specific interfaces are better

5. D – Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) - Depend on abstractions, not concrete classes.
    Meaning: High-level classes should not depend on low-level classes. Both should depend on abstractions (interfaces).
    In simple words: Don’t directly use concrete classes — use interfaces instead.
    Real-life example:  
      Think of a switch and a bulb: 
        Switch should not depend on a specific bulb brand.
        It should work with any device (fan, light, etc.)
    Java idea:
        ❌ Bad: Switch directly uses LightBulb
        ✔ Good: Switch uses Switchable interface
    Bad Example:
        class LightBulb {
            void turnOn() {}
        }
        class Switch {
            LightBulb bulb = new LightBulb();
        }
    Good Example:
        interface Switchable {
            void turnOn();
        }
        class LightBulb implements Switchable {
            public void turnOn() {}
        }
        class Switch {
            Switchable device;
            Switch(Switchable device) {
                this.device = device;
            }
        }
    ✔ Makes code flexible and testable

Why SOLID Matters:
    Easier to maintain
    Easier to test
    Reduces bugs
    Improves scalability

