Shallow Copy vs Deep Copy in Java (Cloning):
 1. Shallow Copy:
    Copies object structure only
    References are shared (not duplicated)
  👉 Means: New object is created .But inner objects (references) point to the same memory
    class Address {
        String city;
        Address(String city) { this.city = city; }
    }
    
    class Person implements Cloneable {
        String name;
        Address address;
    
        Person(String name, Address address) {
            this.name = name;
            this.address = address;
        }
    
        protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
            return super.clone(); // shallow copy
        }
    }

    public class Test {
        public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
            Address addr = new Address("Chennai");
            Person p1 = new Person("John", addr);
    
            Person p2 = (Person) p1.clone();
    
            p2.address.city = "Mumbai";
    
            System.out.println(p1.address.city); // ❌ Mumbai (changed!)
        }
    }
⚠️ Problem: Both objects share the same Address. Changing one → affects the other
🔥 Real-Time Use Case: DTO mapping (fast copy), When objects are immutable

2. Deep Copy
    Copies everything
    Creates new objects for all references
    👉 Means: Completely independent object. No shared references
    real-Time Use Case: Banking systems (avoid shared data) and Multithreading (avoid race conditions)
      class Address {
          String city;
          Address(String city) { this.city = city; }
      }
      
      class Person implements Cloneable {
          String name;
          Address address;
      
          Person(String name, Address address) {
              this.name = name;
              this.address = address;
          }
      
          protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
              Person cloned = (Person) super.clone();
              cloned.address = new Address(this.address.city); // deep copy
              return cloned;
          }
      }
      ✅ Output Behavior
      p2.address.city = "Mumbai";
      System.out.println(p1.address.city); // ✅ Chennai (unchanged)

    Feature        	    Shallow Copy	          Deep Copy
    Object creation    	New object	            New object
    References	        Shared	                New copies
    Performance	        Fast	                  Slower
    Safety	            Risky (side effects)	  Safe
    Default clone()	    Yes	                    No (manual needed)

1. super.clone() → Always shallow- Java default cloning does NOT do deep copy
2. Deep copy must be done manually - You must explicitly clone each reference object
