    Benefit:
        ✔ No ClassCastException
        ✔ Compile-time safety

   1. <T> Usage (Generics): A type parameter (placeholder)
        class Box<T> {
            T value;
            void set(T value) {
                this.value = value;
            }
            T get() {
                return value;
            }
        }
        🔹 Usage : Box<Integer> b = new Box<>(); b.set(10);
        Symbol	    Meaning
        T	        Type
        E	        Element
        K	        Key
        V	        Value

    2. Wildcards (? extends, ? super)
        🔹 ? extends T (Upper Bound)- Accepts T or subclasses of T
                    List<? extends Number> list;
                    ✔ Read allowed
                    ❌ Write not allowed    
        🔹 ? super T (Lower Bound) - Accepts T or superclasses
                    List<? super Integer> list;       
                    ✔ Write allowed
                    ⚠ Read returns Object             
         PECS Principle:
                Producer → extends
                Consumer → super

    3. Type Erasure -Generics are removed at runtime
        🔹 Example
            List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
            At runtime → becomes: List list = new ArrayList();
         Implications - No generic info at runtime
         Cannot do: if(obj instanceof List<String>) ❌
         Why Java uses it? Backward compatibility with old Java versions

 Built-in Annotations:
